  "texts": [
    "To detect spines using skeletons, it is necessary to binarize the original images correctly and extract all spines that are still connected to dendritic shafts.",
    "If any spines become disconnected during the binarization process, they need to be reattached through further processing (Rusakov and Stewart, 1995).",
    "The Rayburst sampling (Rodriguez et al., 2006 (Rodriguez et al.,, 2008)), gradient-based methods (Zhang et al., 2010), and analysis of 3D surfaces (Li and Deng, 2012) represent alternative automated approaches for spine detection.",
    "For spike detection, it is necessary to establish the boundary that separates the spines from the dendritic shafts, using iterative methods (Okabe, 2020).",
    "One way to perform automatic spine segmentation using light microscopy involves a calculation of the distance to the surface of the neuritic shaft for each voxel outside the shaft (Rodriguez et al., 2008; Singh et al., 2017)."
  ],
